ğŸ“˜ What is Inheritance?

Definition:

    Deriving a new class (subclass) from an existing class (superclass) so that the new class acquires all the properties and behaviors (except private members) of the existing class.

    Simple Definition

    Inheritance means one class can use the properties and behavior of another class.

    This helps in reusing code and avoids writing the same code again.

    Key Points:

    Inheritance is an important feature of OOP that provides code reusability.

    Relationship:
        Parent Class â†’ Superclass
        Child Class â†’ Subclass

    Implemented using the extends keyword.

    Example

    class Developer2 extends Developer1 {
       // Developer2 inherits all non-private members of Developer1
    }

ğŸ§¬ Characteristics of Inheritance

    All features of the superclass are automatically available in the subclass.
    Subclass doesnâ€™t need to start coding from scratch.

    Creates a tightly coupled (IS-A) relation â€” changes in the parent affect the child.

    Represents a hierarchical classification:

        Moving upward â†’ more general properties.
        Moving downward â†’ more specific properties.

